To further evaluate the sensing behavior of N-CDs containing 4-NP and HQ, the fluorescence lifetime changes were recorded using the Quantarus-Tauflurescent lifetime measurement system (Fig. 10
                           ). Lifetime changes were evaluated in the presence of different concentrations of analyte and are shown in tabular format (Tables 3 and 4

                           ) for both 4-NP and HQ. As shown in Table 3, the average lifetime of N-CDs in the presence of 4-NP was almost constant up to a concentration of 100 μM. Afterward, the lifetime of N-CDs gradually decreased, dropping from 7.1 ns to 6.6 ns. This indicates that emission quenching includes IFE and dynamic quenching. The Stern-Volmer plot also shows that the distance between the quencher and the fluorophore is smaller. Additionally, the absorption overlay of 4-NP and N-CDs still supports the IFE mechanism. The above observations and discussions can explain that the combination of IFE and dynamic quenching is the reason for N-CDs emission quenching in the presence of 4-NP.

The Langmuir-Hinshelwood process can explain the decolorization of MB by N-CDs. NaBH4 and BH4- of MB are simultaneously adsorbed on the N-CDs surface. After adsorption, BH4
                           − ions transfer electrons to MB through N-CDs. In this case, N-CDs act as an electronic mediator. During this process, a significant amount of H2 gas was generated (Scheme 1
                           ). This outstanding catalytic activity is related to the highly efficient electron-accepting capacity of the produced N-CD [50,51].
